  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This research article, published in PLoS Pathogens, explores the use of viral sequence diversity to estimate HIV infection times in infants, contributing to critical advancements in HIV research and management. Backed by prominent institutions like the University of Nairobi and the University of Washington, the study demonstrates significant potential for downstream reuse, having already enabled further research in related fields.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article titled \"Using viral sequence diversity to estimate time of HIV infection in infants\" provides an innovative approach to HIV research, particularly in understanding the timelines and dynamics of infection in vulnerable populations like infants. As documented in PLoS Pathogens, this work is a testament to the collaboration between reputable institutions such as the University of Nairobi and the University of Washington. This institutional support highlights the importance and validity of the research area.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Financially underpinned by leading funding agencies\u2014including NIH and the Howard Hughes Medical Institute\u2014the study reflects a robust institutional investment in addressing HIV, a global public health challenge. Such backing not only validates the research but also signals its relevance and urgency in the ongoing fight against HIV/AIDS.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although the article has garnered three citations from diverse journals such as Nature Communications and Cell Reports Medicine, it is clear that the research has laid a foundation for further inquiry, since it has proven downstream reuse in four subsequent research efforts. This downstream impact underscores the importance of the data and methodologies presented, enhancing the ecosystem of HIV research.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Furthermore, the commitment to technical reproducibility is evidenced by the presence of a Research Resource Identifier (RRID), which underscores the authors' dedication to fostering transparency and reproducible science in the field. The integration of data repositories, specifically the GitHub Repository, signifies an effort to promote open data practices, allowing for greater accessibility and interaction within the scientific community.</p>",
